Tamika Holmes was settling into her new home in Phoenix when she got the call that too many mothers in Milwaukee receive.

Her 20-year-old daughter, Jahara Kennedy, had been killed.

Kennedy was celebrating her sister's birthday at a hotel in Milwaukee when a group of men tried to rob them. Kennedy was shot during the robbery attempt, Holmes said.

After her daughter’s death, Holmes said she was in denial.

“I just could not believe this was happening,” she said.

Kennedy's 2-year-old son still recognizes his mother's face in pictures, Holmes said in late 2015.

Five months later, Kennedy's brother, Rahkei Washington, was found shot to death inside a car near near N. 62nd St. and W. Villard Ave.

-- By Ashley Luthern

victim.bio:
Gervonni Sherrod was pregnant with her fifth child when her son Vonnae Whitaker was killed on Jan. 13, 2015.

She said her pregnancy turned out to be a kind of a blessing in two ways – bringing her a new child and forcing her to focus on the life that was to be and not break down over the life lost.

Vonnae, 19, and Sherrod’s 15-year-old nephew were trying to buy marijuana when they were shot by Jarvell Little, 17. The nephew survived.

Little was convicted of second degree reckless homicide and sentenced to 12 years in prison.

Vonnae’s father had died just four months earlier, Sherrod said. He and Vonnae are buried side-by-side at Graceland cemetery.

She said Children’s Hospital tried several times to get her and children -- ages 23, 13 and 10 -- to group counseling, but she said she didn’t feel ready, and wanted to find some individual counseling first. They eventually found support via Facebook survivor groups, she said.

She held a candle light vigil Sept. 17, Vonnae’s birthday.

“Tons of people came out,” she said, “even in the rain. I was like, ‘Wow, what a relief.”

-- By Bruce Vielmetti

victim.bio:
Durrell Anderson says his younger brother Terrance used to brag about his job on a Gulf of Mexico oil rig to friends back in Milwaukee, "How many people you know take a helicopter to work?"

Anderson was a cook on the rigs for months at a time, but didn't get sent back out after his last home leave in late 2014 because his blood pressure was too high, Durrell said, so he came to Milwaukee and was helping out at his brother's bar, New Entertainers Lounge, in February.

Durrell, 54, said he'd owned the bar on Green Tree Road about three years without any problems before Feb. 8, 2015. Sitting at the lounge in November 2015, while it was closed for remodeling, he recounted watching his brother get shot while trying to keep order.

Four men were walking out near bar time, Durrell said, when they seemed to be pressuring a woman to come with them. Terrance went over to ask the men to move on, and as they got near the door, one fired a shot into the ceiling, then blindly pointed back inside and fired again, hitting Terrance twice, all caught on video.

Next, the shooter killed another patron, Desha Robertson, in the entryway to the bar, the group's original target, Durrell said he later learned from detectives. All the bullet holes were still visible.

Pierre Cardell Brown, 29, pleaded guilty in December to two counts of second degree reckless homicide. His sentencing is scheduled for Feb. 26.

After the killings, Durrell said he considered selling the business, but then thought of the good times he enjoyed there with Terrance, who left behind a girlfriend and an adult daughter, as well as a younger brother and sister.

Durrell said he went through counseling, got involved with After the Violence and hosted First Friday support sessions at his business last summer.

He found the process helpful, but still doesn't know what to make of young people who resort to gun violence.

"It's like they've been robbed of their compassion, their imaginations," he said, and the only emotion they know is anger.

"This is a like a plague," he said of the killers. "They're like suicide bombers without any religion."

-- By Bruce Vielmetti

victim.bio:
In 2002, Laron Ball was fatally shot by a detective in a Milwaukee courtroom as he tried to escape from custody.

Thirteen years later, in February of last year, his brother, Latrail Ball, also was fatally shot, but in very different circumstance.

Latrail Ball, 26, was killed in a drive-by shooting, allegedly by a member of a notorious Milwaukee gang on Feb. 8, 2015.

On Jan. 11, 2016, a jury convicted Christopher Ross, 26, who policy say was a member of the Wild 100s gang, in the slaying of Ball.

From court documents, it appears Ball may not have been the intended target. Ross had gotten into a dispute with another man at a bar. After he left, the man’s truck got stuck in the snow.

Ball stopped to help the man, whom he knew. Ross drove up a short time later and opened fire, according to the complaint.

Police recovered the murder weapon when a police informant purchased the gun.

In May 2002, Laron Ball, 20, was on trial for felony murder and armed robbery. Extra security was in put in place because of his violent reputation but on the day of the verdict, he was not wearing a stun belt.

As the guilty verdicts were read, Ball jumped over a table and tried to break a window. He was tackled by a sheriff’s deputy. Ball got one of their guns and shot a deputy. A police detective ultimately shot and killed Ball.

-- By John Diedrich

victim.bio:
Lennair Davis was a good, sweet grandmother who took care of her children and grandchildren every way she could.

She was doing that when she died.

One morning last February, Davis, 56, was climbing into a van to accompany her son to court when another car pulled up. Someone inside that vehicle opened fire and sped away.

The presumed target, Howard D. Davis, was not injured. His mother was killed.

The homicide is the latest in what appears to be case of violent retaliation.

At the time his mother was shot, Howard Davis was on trial with another man in the fatal shooting of Raymond E. Harris Jr.

Harris, in turn, was suspected of shooting Howard Davis in summer 2013, according to a criminal complaint.

Howard Davis was convicted and sentenced to 40 years in prison in Harris’ death. No one has been arrested in the death of his mother, Lennair.

Callie Jones said her mother loved playing pool, dancing, listening to music and especially cooking.

“She would cook stuff you never heard of in your life but it was the best thing you ever had. Mama cooked for anyone and everyone,” Jones said.

“She was the sweetest person in the world.”

Jones, who also was in the van the day of the shooting in the 4500 block of N. 28th St., said she is certain the bullet was meant for her brother.

Homicide touched the the family again three months after Lennair’s death when Jones’ cousin, Pedrell Davis, was fatally stabbed.

“It’s been an overwhelming year,” Jones said in December 2015. “I can’t wait for it to be over.”

-- By John Diedrich

Ericka Walker was achieving her dreams of becoming a recording artist, said her mother, Michelle Walker.

Although she had signed with a record label in Atlanta, Ericka loved Milwaukee -- loved it enough to get parts of the city skyline tattooed on her, her mother said.

“I thought of all the places in the world, she would be safe here,” she said.

Ericka, 19, was wounded multiples times when gunfire rang out during an argument at a house party in the 3200 block of N. 35th St.

During the argument, one man was pulled into a bedroom, where Walker and another person tried to hold him back from returning to the fight. A spray of bullets hit the door and hit Ericka on the other side.

Jovan T. Mull — who already was charged with shooting a woman during a separate armed robbery — was charged in June 2015 with first-degree reckless homicide in Ericka's killing.

"it just seems like the city is stained after what happened to my daughter," Michelle said.

-- By Ashley Luthern

victim.bio:
Aaron Harmon’s family didn’t celebrate Christmas or New Year’s. They haven’t had a holiday party since Aaron, 26, was shot to death on Easter 2015.

“We didn’t do any holidays because we’re used to doing them together,” said his mother, Anisha Harmon. “We’re just incomplete. It’s like having a puzzle and missing a piece. It’s crazy.”

Afraid she would lose her job and knowing she would need to pay for a funeral, Anisha went to work the day after Aaron was killed following an argument outside a tavern. Another man, Jeremey T. Green, 33, also died, mistakenly shot in the back by one of his friends.

Anisha still hasn’t picked up her son’s ashes from the funeral home because she can’t afford the urn.

Aaron’s identical twin, Evan, was wounded during the same argument. When she rushed to the scene in the early morning hours, Anisha didn’t know which son was at the hospital and which was under a tarp in the street.

Aaron also leaves behind a 3-year-old son, a 15-year-old brother, an 11-year-old sister and a baby brother born two months after the shooting.

The baby was premature and the delivery was difficult, Anisha said. She left the hospital against medical advice because she worried Evan wasn’t equipped to care for the other kids due to the emotional trauma of being shot and watching his twin brother die.

As for Anisha, she said she has not yet had the luxury of time to mourn her son.

“You’ve got to be normal for everybody else,” she said. “You just stiffen up. You’ve still got to go to work, check on the baby, keep the 11-year-old and the 15-year-old on track with their activities. I have yet to sit down and say, ‘My son is gone. How do I adjust?’”

More than anything, she wishes people would think before they make the decision to take someone’s life, a split-second choice with a far-reaching impact.

“You’re affecting a whole community. Now our community is missing something,” she said. “It’s missing you. It’s missing him. And it was so senseless.”

-- By Gina Barton

victim.bio:
Latrice Morgan lost her protector When Willie Woods Jr., 22, was shot to death at a neighborhood barbecue in April.

Morgan, 25, who suffers from cerebral palsy, has used a wheelchair all her life. The way Woods cared for her allowed her to move out of her mother’s house for the first time.

“He took care of her every need,” said Morgan’s mother, Louisa Nelson. “If she needed something to eat, he took care of that. Needed to shower, he took care of that. He made her feel more independent."

"She didn’t need to live with mom. Didn’t need to call mom.”

The night Woods died, Morgan waited in her wheelchair until nearly midnight for him to come home and help her into bed. Instead, the police came to her door. But because she was not a blood relative, they wouldn’t tell her what happened, Nelson said.

She told them where to find his family, and they came to pick her up after they got the news, fearing the bad elements in the neighborhood would know she was alone and vulnerable now that her boyfriend was gone.

“Knowing that she’s in the position she’s in, and then for him to be taken from her. That’s real difficult,” Nelson said. “She feels like her life is basically over.”

The man who killed Woods with a shot to the chest, Eugene L. Patterson, 46, was sentenced to prison in January 2016 after being convicted of first-degree reckless homicide.

As for Morgan, she had to move back in with her mother. After a couple of months, Nelson hurt her back and Morgan had to move again. She now lives with one of Woods’ sisters.

“He protected my daughter,” Nelson said of Woods. “He protected her like crazy.”

-- By Gina Barton

victim.bio:
Every year, artist and activist Patricia Ann Wilson makes an altar to mark the Day of the Dead, a Latin American holiday of remembrance.

Last fall, her project featured images of Trayvon Martin, Michael Brown and others who died in high-profile incidents. It also featured a collage of her younger brother, Marcus D. Wilson, 51, of Milwaukee.

Marcus was beaten to death in May, his body burned and left under the bridge at 29th St. and Kinnickinnic Ave., she said.

The case remains unsolved, leaving Patricia frustrated that she has no answer to why someone brutally killed and mutilated her brother, a sweet, kind man who loved making music.

“He did not read music. He would always listen to my albums, listen to music and sit down at his keyboard and go play it,” she said.

Both of their parents were alcoholics, leading to a difficult childhood for Patricia, Marcus and two other siblings, she said. Patricia and Marcus bonded because both were artists, and he moved in with her when she was 24 and he was 16.

In the end, Marcus, like his parents, struggled with alcoholism and was living on the streets for a time, Patricia said. She was working to bring him to Seattle when he was murdered.

Not long after that, Patricia was in line at the grocery store and glanced into the cooler to see a label that read, “Share a Coke with Marcus.”

She was stunned.

“I think he was trying to tell me that he’s here with me,” she said.

-- By Gina Barton

victim.bio:
About a year ago, Jeremy J. Hollins and his brother, Bryan, were driving when they spotted a middle school-aged boy standing at a freezing bus stop.

“My brother had on a peacoat, and the kid had on a thin windbreaker,” Bryan recalled. “Jeremy gave him his jacket. We rolled off, and that little boy was looking at him like, ‘What just happened?’ He was startled, but we could tell it was a blessing.”

Although he had spent time in prison before his death in May, there were other sides to Jeremy, 28, that not many people knew about, his brother said.

“He loved kids,” Bryan said. “I watched him feed a whole block of kids, take them to the movies, buy them clothes for school. When it comes to kids and elderly, he’ll lay down the red carpet for them because he knows they’re innocent.”

The two brothers had many conversations about Greek mythology, history and larger-than-life political figures, such as Hugo Chavez, Fidel Castro and Che Guevara.

“People never let him express that side of him. He didn’t want to share that side of his intellect because he didn’t know how certain people would receive it,” Bryan said.

The death of his brother, who was shot to death after taking a phone call and stepping outside a house, has left Bryan, 26, contemplating a move out west, away from his close-knit family and the city where he grew up.

“I just feel it’s a broken system here, but then again it starts with us,” he said. “I’m disappointed with my community, with my culture as well. If we’re not holding hands together, why are we staying? I’m just fed up. I’m angry.

“This community needs to see the greater good in people.”

-- By Gina Barton

A year ago, Tamika Holmes settling in to her new home in Phoenix when she got the call that too many Milwaukee mothers receive.

Her 20-year-old daughter, Jahara Kennedy, had been killed.

Kennedy was celebrating her sister’s birthday at a hotel in Milwaukee when four men tried to rob them. Kennedy barricaded herself behind a closed door. One of the men shot through the door, and a bullet hit Kennedy in the head.

Holmes, who had moved to Phoenix for a new job, tried to convince her son, 19-year-old Rahkei Washington, to to join her there. He told her couldn’t leave the city where his sister was buried.

He had gotten into a trouble a few years ago and spent time at Lincoln Hills School for Boys, but since then he had graduated from high school, taken the SAT and applied to college.

Then Holmes got another call: Her son was found shot to death inside a car near near N. 62nd St. and W. Villard Ave. in June — just five months after his sister was killed.

It was a college in Texas checking to make sure Washington had received his acceptance letter.

Those who knew Ilona Gonzalez remember her as a caring, driven woman.

Shortly before her death, Gonzalez, 30, had started teaching a writing course at her alma mater, Alverno College, her friend, Holly McCoy, said.

“She hadn’t even reached her full potential and she had already done so much,” McCoy said. “She has so much more to give the world. I just hope that people focus on her life.”

McCoy, a mother of five, and Gonzalez, who is survived by her 9-year-old son, bonded during their graduate classes at Alverno College and with their work for the local chapter of the Young Nonprofit Professionals Network.

Gonzalez also volunteered for the Benedict Center, a Milwaukee nonprofit that helps women involved in the criminal justice system.

Before pursuing her master's degree, Gonzalez earned her undergraduate degree in professional communications.

"She stood out as one of the best students I've encountered in more than 30 years of teaching," said Dawn Balistreri, an associate professor at Alverno College.

The entire college was devastated by her loss, she said.

"She always took the time to help me, to help other students and help her colleagues," Balistreri said.

Gonzalez's 35-year-old husband has been charged in her homicide.

-- By Ashley Luthern

victim.bio:
Herman Davis loved to bowl.

But 39 years of working snowplows for Douglas Dynamics, Inc. took a toll on his body, leaving him with poor circulation and lacking the ability to play the sport he enjoyed so much, said his daughter, Felicia Givens.

Rather than abandon the world of strikes and gutter balls he and his wife found so much joy in, he took on the role of scorekeeper and cheerleader, happy just to be involved, Givens said.

His talent with arithmetic gave him an edge in the scorekeeping game.

“That man was amazing with numbers,” Givens said. “He was a walking calculator.”

She remembers her father helping with math homework at the kitchen table, an experience her own children will not have with their grandfather.

Davis was fatally stabbed in an alley on October 4, 2016, during an altercation with a man whose car was blocking the way to Davis’ garage.

He got out of his vehicle to confront the man and was stabbed in the chest, police said. He was 73 years old.

Police charged Deondre Marquis Dean, then 31, with second-degree reckless homicide for the stabbing, which Dean told police was an act of self-defense. A jury found Dean not guilty, acquitting him of the homicide charge. Dean has since been charged with other unrelated offenses.

Givens said the loss of her father is remains an open wound for her and her family, particularly her daughters.

“My children still dealing with it,” she said. “My girls gravitated more to my father than anyone.”

Davis was an avid outdoorsmen and his granddaughters were among his closest fishing buddies. Givens said her daughters and nieces were always eager to accompany Davis to the lake.

Givens said her father was a man of many talents, a self-proclaimed carpenter and a valuable asset to the men’s chorus. He sang “loud as all get out,” she said.

Givens said she best remembers her father’s laugh and his smile.

“My daddy had a really jovial laugh and a smile that would light up any room,” she said.

-- By Morgan Hughes

victim.bio:
“I can still see his face and his eyes,” Annie Smith-Deramus said, remembering the soft grey tone of her late husband, Kenneth Deramus’, iris’.

Kenneth was beaten into a coma in his driveway Feb. 18 during what his family believes was an attempted carjacking. He suffered multiple fractures to his face, a broken nose and brain bleeding.

Nearly two months into the coma, it became clear to Smith-Dermaus that she would never see those eyes again. He died April 7. He was 62.

His family said he knew his attacker, Dorian Ramsey, who after the assault was charged with aggravated battery, and after Kenneth’s death, amended charges for homicide.

In the wake of the loss, Smith-Deramus said she’s grateful to be able to remember him. His deep love for music, his unwavering desire to please other people and his endless energy.

And she thinks about before.

They met in less than ideal circumstances. The two were staying at a family support center, she with her three children, he with his daughter. But despite their situations, Smith-Deramus said they found comfort in each other.

“He made me feel comfortable in an uncomfortable situation.”

She was a transplant from Chicago and Milwaukee did not yet feel like her home, but Kenneth changed that. He became her personal tour guide. Her favorite memory from those days is being shown the Milwaukee lakefront for the first time.

She admits she was leery of Kenneth at first. “I just thought he was full of hot air,” she said. But he proved her skepticism unnecessary. Their friendship eventually grew into a marriage, and they wed to an Al Green gospel song on Feb. 14, 2006. Valentine’s Day.

“I’m not gonna make him more than he was,” she said. “There was good and bad, there’s good and bad in everyone, but he was full of love.”

“I’ve seen him drag himself out of bed to go help a friend at 2 a.m.,” she continued. “When he was there for you, he was really in your corner.”

She said while not everyone knew that side of him, it was the side she knew best.

They were living apart when he died. The last time they spoke, Smith-Deramus said she told Kenneth, “Whenever you’re ready you know you can come home.”

She said Kenneth was a father to her children, whether he was living in their home or not, and that no matter what happened between them, their friendship never waned.

To memorialize him, they installed a glass-topped table in their home with photos of Kenneth with his and her children.

“When you sit at that table, you see him and us as a family,” she said. “I wouldn’t change my life, not one ounce. Not one ounce.”

-- Morgan Hughes

victim.bio:
He was a jokester, he loved to dance and he tried to sing, Caprice Williams said, laughing at the memory of her son’s off-pitch melodies. Food was another constant. Every time she spoke to him, he was cooking something new.

This is how Williams remembers her son, Jimmie R. Williams Jr., who was fatally shot April 21, 2018, near 18th and Locust streets. He was taken to a fire station by an anonymous driver who fled after leaving him at the station.

Although firefighters were able to keep him alive and take him to a nearby hospital, Jimmie died from his injuries five days later. He was 25.

Williams said her tight-knit family is grieving hard. One of seven siblings, Jimmie was “the baby” to three older brothers and a guardian to two younger sisters and a younger brother. She said his siblings are sad and angry over the loss.

“Their brother was murdered and no one is in custody,” Williams said.

The Milwaukee County Medical Examiner ruled Jimmie’s death a homicide, and the Milwaukee Police Department are still seeking suspects in the case.

Williams said that her son had big plans for himself and his family, having just moved back into his childhood home the day before the shooting. He wanted to renovate it and raise his children in the home where he had grown up.

He had four sons, ages 1, 3, 5 and 6, with another on the way.

“I’ll always tell them how much he loved them,” Williams said, “He was a great father.”

On Father’s Day, the family held a memorial outside of the home Jimmie had hoped to watch his children grow up in. They turned a large white ash tree at the front of the house into a shrine, fastening photos, posters and balloons to its trunk.

Williams said she doesn’t think she will ever come to terms with the loss of her child.

“I don’t think I could ever get closure,” she said. “I don’t even know what that would feel like.”

- By Morgan Hughes

From ME's office:

This tentatively identified 47-year-old female was found in an advanced stage of decomposition in the upper unit of a duplex that
she reportedly resided in. The unit sustained massive damage in a fire on 04/11/2021, and the decedent was not found until
07/09/2021 when a restoration company was cleaning out the unit. The circumstances surrounding the fire are suspicious.

I received a call from Lt. Gena Malanche with the City of Milwaukee Police Department Criminal Investigations Bureau, reporting
the discovery of unidentified human remains found at the address of 4425A North 67th Street Milwaukee, WI 53218. The body
was discovered in the upper unit of a duplex-style home at the aforementioned address. According to Lt. Malanche, the residence
was involved in a fire on 04/11/2021. The incident was recorded on 04/11/2021 at 2236 hours. The incident was handled by the
City of Milwaukee Fire Department, and the City of Milwaukee Police Department was reportedly requested to handle traffic
control only. There is no MPD incident number associated with the fire on 04/11/21. On today's date, employees with Fire
Recovery, a fire damage restoration service, were at the residence to perform cleanup services. The body was discovered in a rear
bedroom on the second floor of the duplex. According to the employee with Fire Recovery, the body was not initially observed as it was covered with numerous items of debris. When the debris was moved, the body was located. It is unknown if the body
sustained any thermal injuries related to the fire as it also appeared to be in an advanced stage of decomposition. I informed Lt.
Malanche that I would be responding to the scene. -M. Martin

Deputies originally responded to the BP gas station at 281 W. Main Street at 7:41 pm, for a report of a woman asking people for money and a ride. Deputies were able to locate the woman, Angelina J. Ruesch, age 28, at 277 W. Main Street. She displayed a handgun and refused to follow commands from the deputies. A Taser was deployed, but was ineffective. Sheriff’s deputies were ultimately able to disarm her and safely take her into custody. Detectives then searched a vehicle Ruesch was traveling in, which was found parked near the Piggly Wiggly grocery store on Jefferson Street. A deceased person was located concealed inside of the vehicle, but evidence suggested the death occurred at a different location. Crime scene investigators from the Dane County Sheriff’s Office and the Milwaukee Police Department have been processing evidence at the scene. Ruesch has been booked into the Dane County Jail on a probation hold, but is also facing tentative charges in Dane County for Recklessly Endangering Safety, Resisting While Armed, Disorderly Conduct While Armed and Carrying a Concealed Weapon. MILWAUKEE, WI - On Sunday, January 23, 2022, at approximately 3:45 p.m., Milwaukee Police Department (MPD) officers responded to a welfare check at a residence located on the 2500 block of N. 21st Street. Upon arrival, officers entered the residence and located six deceased individuals. All the victims sustained gunshot injuries.



MPD detectives have been working tirelessly to solve this case since these events unfolded. We have been relentlessly following up on all leads. At this time, we can report that we have four persons of interest in custody. The persons of interest are all adults. We are still trying to determine what their involvement was, if any, with the homicides. No charges have been referred to the DA’s Office at this time.



Based on evidence at the scene and our ongoing investigation, we believe there were multiple suspects involved in this incident. The time this incident occurred still remains undetermined.

On Monday, we became aware of a 911 call that was considered to be related to this investigation but was not attributed to the address where the incident occurred. This 911 caller claimed that she was a victim of a shooting and that multiple other people were shot. The caller gave two different addresses in the vicinity of where the homicides occurred but neither were on the 2500 block of N. 21st Street.



This call was received approximately 12 hours prior to the discovery of the victims. Officers were dispatched to both locations; however, they did not locate any evidence of a shooting and were unable to contact the caller. Eventually, we were able to locate the person who made that call and we were able to determine she was not a victim of a shooting. Her connection to this incident remains under investigation.



MPD continues to ask for assistance from the public for any information regarding this incident. Anyone with any information is asked to please call Milwaukee Police at (414) 935-7360 or to remain anonymous, contact Crime Stoppers at (414) 224-TIPS or P3 Tips App.



The Milwaukee Police Department sends our sincere condolences to the victims’ families, friends and neighbors that were impacted by this horrific incident. Our community deserves better. This senseless violence needs to stop. The entire Milwaukee Police Department remains committed to working with all our partners, most importantly, you, the community

Press release from Khalif Rainey:

On Monday (May 16) someone shot a 31-year-old legally blind man just before 11:30 p.m. at N. 37th and W. Burleigh. First responders took him to the hospital where he died of his injuries.

I am saddened by this senseless murder, and I offer my prayers and condolences to the loved ones and friends of the victim. His family described the man as kind and funny, and just days away from his 32nd birthday when he was shot.

Gun violence of ANY kind is heinous and unwarranted, but I am especially angered that someone would decide to open fire on a person with diminished capacities. What kind of person would do such a thing?!

I am asking the public to help us capture and bring the shooter to justice as soon as possible.

Anyone with any information is asked to contact Milwaukee Police at (414) 935-7360 or to remain anonymous, contact Crime Stoppers at (414) 224-Tips or P3 Tips App.
